					<msContents class="#MTM">
						<summary><p>A multi-text (possibly composite) manuscript, entitled <title xml:lang="ta">Akattiyar Aintu</title> ("Five [works] of Akattiyar") according to Cabaton (1912), containing 5 different works of Akattiyar and the following codicological units:
  <list rend="numbered">
									<item>The <title xml:lang="ta">Akasttiyar aruḷicceytap pūṟaṇacūsttiram</title> ("Treatise on the fullness  graciously composed  by Akasttiyar"). One folio (only recto) without foliation (U1). Possibly a prefatory part to the next unit (U2), by another hand.</item>
									<item>The <title xml:lang="ta">Akattiyamakāmuṉicuvāmiy aruḷiya pūraṇacūṣttiram</title>, enlisted as <title xml:lang="ta">Pūraṇacūttiram</title> ("Treatise on the fullness") on the additional <locus facs="453">title page</locus>. It appears to be a text on yogic and religious practices, as well as alchemical preparations, consisting of 215 enumerated verses (U2).</item>
									<item>A blank folio (U3), probably misplaced in the bundle, as it interrupts the continuous foliation.</item>
									<item>The <title xml:lang="ta">Akaṣttiyamakāmuṉi aruḷicceyita tīṣṣaiviti yirunūṟu</title>, that is, <title xml:lang="ta">Tīṣṣāviti</title> ("Rules of initiation"). It appears to be a text on religious and alchemical practices, composed  in 214 verses (U4).</item>
									<item>The <title xml:lang="ta">Akaṣttiyar ñāṉam</title> ("Knowledge by Agastya"), which seems to be a text on religious and alchemical practices in 100 verses (U5).</item>
									<item>The <title xml:lang="ta">Akaṣttiyar vātacūṣttiram 200</title>, "Alchemical treatise" (<foreign xml:lang="ta">vātacūttiram</foreign>), which appears to be a text on alchemy and medicine in 202 verses (U6).</item>
									<item>An incomplete <title xml:lang="ta">Pūcāviti</title> ("Rules of worship"), which appears to be a text on yoga and religious practices in 201 verses. The beginning of the text is missing; the text in the manuscript starts with verse 138. (U7).</item>
								</list></p>
							<p>Description based on the digital images available on Gallica.</p>
							<p>Dimensions after Cabaton (1912).</p>
						</summary>

						
						
						
						
						
						
						
